INSERT INTO `species_strain` VALUES (553,'Pantoea ananatis',53335,'Y',0,'bases','Pantoea is a genus of Gram-negative bacteria of the family Enterobacteriaceae, recently separated from the Enterobacter genus. Pantoea ananatis is a common epiphyte; it also occurs endophytically in hosts where it has been reported to cause disease symptoms and in hosts where no such symptoms have been described. Pantoea ananatis causes disease symptoms in a wide range of economically important agricultural crops and forest tree species worldwide. Its unconventional nature lies in the fact that, unlike the majority of plant pathogenic microbes, P. ananatis is capable of infecting humans','heterotrophic','organotrophic','chemotrophic'),(66270,'Pantoea stewartii subsp. indologenes',53335,'Y',4681235,'bases','\0P\0a\0n\0t\0o\0e\0a\0 \0s\0t\0e\0w\0a\0r\0t\0i\0i\0 \0i\0s\0 \0a\0 \0n\0o\0n\0m\0o\0t\0i\0l\0e\0,\0 \0f\0a\0c\0u\0l\0t\0a\0t\0i\0v\0e\0 \0a\0n\0a\0e\0r\0o\0b\0i\0c\0,\0 \0g\0r\0a\0m\0 \0n\0e\0g\0a\0t\0i\0v\0e\0,\0 \0r\0o\0d\0-\0s\0h\0a\0p\0e\0d\0 \0b\0a\0c\0t\0e\0r\0i\0u\0m\0 \0t\0h\0a\0t\0 \0c\0a\0u\0s\0e\0s\0 \0S\0t\0e\0w\0a\0r\0t \0s\0 \0w\0i\0l\0t\0 \0a\0n\0d\0 \0l\0e\0a\0f\0 \0b\0l\0i\0g\0h\0t\0 \0d\0i\0s\0e\0a\0s\0e\0 \0o\0n\0 \0m\0a\0i\0z\0e\0 \0(\0p\0a\0r\0t\0i\0c\0u\0l\0a\0r\0l\0y\0 \0s\0w\0e\0e\0t\0 \0c\0o\0r\0n\0)\0,\0 \0f\0l\0i\0n\0t\0,\0 \0d\0e\0n\0t\0,\0 \0f\0l\0o\0w\0e\0r\0,\0 \0a\0n\0d\0 \0p\0o\0p\0c\0o\0r\0n\0.\0 \0P\0a\0n\0t\0o\0e\0a\0 \0b\0a\0c\0t\0e\0r\0i\0a\0 \0a\0r\0e\0 \0y\0e\0l\0l\0o\0w\0 \0p\0i\0g\0m\0e\0n\0t\0e\0d\0,\0 \0f\0e\0r\0m\0e\0n\0t\0 \0l\0a\0c\0t\0o\0s\0e\0,\0 \0a\0r\0e\0 \0m\0o\0t\0i\0l\0e\0,\0 \0a\0n\0d\0 \0f\0o\0r\0m\0 \0m\0u\0c\0o\0i\0d\0 \0c\0o\0l\0o\0n\0i\0e\0s\0.\0 \0B\0e\0s\0i\0d\0e\0s\0 \0t\0h\0a\0t\0,\0 \0s\0o\0m\0e\0 \0o\0f\0 \0t\0h\0e\0 \0s\0p\0e\0c\0i\0e\0s\0 \0s\0h\0o\0w\0 \0q\0u\0o\0r\0u\0m\0 \0s\0e\0n\0s\0i\0n\0g\0 \0a\0b\0i\0l\0i\0t\0y\0 \0t\0h\0a\0t\0 \0c\0o\0u\0l\0d\0 \0d\0r\0i\0v\0e\0 \0d\0i\0f\0f\0e\0r\0e\0n\0t\0 \0g\0e\0n\0e\0 \0e\0x\0p\0r\0e\0s\0s\0i\0o\0n\0 \0h\0e\0n\0c\0e\0 \0c\0o\0n\0t\0r\0o\0l\0l\0i\0n\0g\0 \0c\0e\0r\0t\0a\0i\0n\0 \0p\0h\0y\0s\0i\0o\0l\0o\0g\0i\0c\0a\0l\0 \0a\0c\0t\0i\0v\0i\0t\0i\0e\0s\0.','heterotrophic','organotrophic','chemotrophic'),(95614,'Curtobacterium sp. B18',2034,'Y',3713770,'bases','Curtobacterium is a genus of bacteria of the order Actinomycetales. They are Gram-positive soil organisms. Known to cause diseases in plants','heterotrophic','organotrophic lithotrophic','chemotrophic'),(134560,'Nocardioides sp. C157',1839,'N',0,'bases','The genus Nocardioides was proposed by Prauser (1976) for Gram-positive, non-acid-fast, aerobic, and mesophilic nocardioform actinomycetes, developing a mycelium that fragments into irregular rod- to coccus-like elements. Strain C157 showed close phylogenic relationships with Nocardioides SP12. Have been isolated from a variety of habitats including soils, herbage, an oil shale colummn, industrial wastewater and hyper-saline lakes','heterotrophic','organotrophic lithotrophic','chemotrophic'),(189451,'Papiliotrema bandonii',189450,'N',0,'bases','\0P\0a\0p\0i\0l\0i\0o\0t\0r\0e\0m\0a\0 \0i\0s\0 \0a\0 \0g\0e\0n\0u\0s\0 \0o\0f\0 \0f\0u\0n\0g\0i\0 \0i\0n\0 \0t\0h\0e\0 \0f\0a\0m\0i\0l\0y\0 \0T\0r\0e\0m\0e\0l\0l\0a\0c\0e\0a\0e\0.\0 \0T\0h\0e\0 \0g\0e\0n\0u\0s\0 \0i\0s\0 \0m\0o\0n\0o\0t\0y\0p\0i\0c\0,\0 \0c\0o\0n\0t\0a\0i\0n\0i\0n\0g\0 \0t\0h\0e\0 \0s\0i\0n\0g\0l\0e\0 \0s\0p\0e\0c\0i\0e\0s\0 \0P\0a\0p\0i\0l\0i\0o\0t\0r\0e\0m\0a\0 \0b\0a\0n\0d\0o\0n\0i\0i\0,\0 \0f\0o\0u\0n\0d\0 \0i\0n\0 \0P\0o\0r\0t\0u\0g\0a\0l\0.\0  \0P\0a\0p\0i\0l\0i\0o  \0 \0r\0e\0f\0e\0r\0s\0 \0t\0o\0 \0t\0h\0e\0 \0b\0u\0t\0t\0e\0r\0f\0l\0y\0-\0l\0i\0k\0e\0 \0s\0h\0a\0p\0e\0 \0o\0f\0 \0t\0h\0e\0 \0c\0o\0n\0i\0d\0i\0a\0,\0   \0t\0r\0e\0m\0a \0 \0r\0e\0f\0e\0r\0s\0 \0t\0o\0 \0t\0h\0e\0 \0t\0r\0e\0m\0e\0l\0l\0a\0c\0e\0o\0u\0s\0 \0n\0a\0t\0u\0r\0e\0 \0o\0f\0 \0t\0h\0i\0s\0 \0f\0u\0n\0g\0u\0s\0.\0 \0T\0h\0e\0 \0c\0o\0m\0p\0o\0u\0n\0d\0 \0h\0a\0s\0 \0f\0e\0m\0i\0n\0i\0n\0e\0 \0g\0e\0n\0d\0e\0r\0.','heterotrophic','organotrophic','chemotrophic'),(293386,'Bacillus stratosphericus',1386,'Y',3733110,'bases','B. stratosphericus is a motile rod-shaped, gram positive bacterium. It is endospore-forming, as many Bacillus are, and is able to withstand unfavourable conditions, permitting it to colonize and adapt to variable environments. B. stratosphericus can be detected in the stratosphere orbiting the Earth among satellites. However, B. stratosphericus is not limited to the atmosphere and can be found in an array of environments such as desert soils, deep seas and estuaries.','heterotrophic','organotrophic lithotrophic','chemotrophic'),(367110,'Neurospora crassa OR74A',5140,'Y',37097299,'bases','A type of red bread mold of the phylum Ascomycota. The genus name, meaning \"nerve spore\" refers to the characteristic striations on the spores. N. crassa is used as a model organism because it is easy to grow and has a haploid life cycle that makes genetic analysis simple since recessive traits will show up in the offspring. Analysis of genetic recombination is facilitated by the ordered arrangement of the products of meiosis in Neurospora ascospores. Its entire genome of seven chromosomes has been sequenced. In its natural environment, N. crassa lives mainly in tropical and sub-tropical regions.It can be found growing on dead plant matter after fires.','heterotrophic','organotrophic','chemotrophic'),(375700,'Bacillus sp. G2DM-32',1386,'N',0,'bases','Bacilli are rod-shaped, Gram-positive, sporulating, aerobes or facultative anaerobes. Most bacilli are saprophytes. Each bacterium creates only one spore, which is resistant to heat, cold, radiation, desiccation, and disinfectants. Bacilli exhibit an array of physiologic abilities that allow them to live in a wide range of habitats, including many extreme habitats such as desert sands, hot springs, and Arctic soils. Species in the genus Bacillus can be thermophilic, psychrophilic, acidophilic, alkaliphilic, halotolerant, or halophilic and are capable at growing at pH values, temperatures, and salt concentrations where few other organisms can survive.','heterotrophic','organotrophic lithotrophic','chemotrophic'),(436913,'Erwinia sp. CU208',551,'N',0,'bases','Erwinia is a Gram-negative, rod-shaped bacterium that lives alone or aggregates into pairs and chains. Non-spore forming and peritrichously flagellated, Erwinia carotovora produces a number of extracellular plant cell wall degrading enzymes such as pectic enzymes that degrade pectin, cellulase that degrades cellulose, hemicellulases, arabanases, cyanoses and a protease. As a mesophilic bacterium, Erwinia thrives the most in the temperature range between 27 and 30 degrees Celsius.','heterotrophic','organotrophic lithotrophic','chemotrophic'),(443224,'Paraconiothyrium sp. WL-2',300251,'N',0,'bases','These fungi are of great societal interest because several species are known plant pathogens, biological control agents, bioremediators, and producers of metabolites with antimicrobial capabilities. Promotes oxidation of highly reactive oxidants in soil, such as Mn(III/IV) and can promote wood degradation. For further information please consult the Coniothyrium genus as the Paraconiothyrium genus is new and not well written on.','heterotrophic','organotrophic lithotrophic','chemotrophic'),(450181,'Cladosporium bruhnei',5498,'N',0,'bases','Cladosporium is a genus of fungi including some of the most common indoor and outdoor molds. Species produce olive-green to brown or black colonies, and have dark-pigmented conidia that are formed in simple or branching chains.','heterotrophic','organotrophic','chemotrophic'),(570416,'Bacillus thuringiensis serovar kurstaki YBT-1520',1386,'Y',6520413,'bases','\0B\0a\0c\0i\0l\0l\0u\0s\0 \0T\0h\0u\0r\0i\0n\0g\0i\0e\0n\0s\0i\0s\0 \0i\0s\0 \0a\0 \0G\0r\0a\0m\0-\0p\0o\0s\0i\0t\0i\0v\0e\0,\0 \0s\0o\0i\0l\0-\0d\0w\0e\0l\0l\0i\0n\0g\0 \0b\0a\0c\0t\0e\0r\0i\0u\0m\0,\0 \0c\0o\0m\0m\0o