\0n\0s\0,\0 \0t\0h\0o\0u\0g\0h\0,\0 \0d\0o\0 \0n\0o\0t\0 \0h\0a\0v\0e\0 \0i\0n\0s\0e\0c\0t\0i\0c\0i\0d\0a\0l\0 \0p\0r\0o\0p\0e\0r\0t\0i\0e\0s\0.','heterotrophic','organotrophic lithotrophic','chemotrophic'),(596312,'Micrococcus luteus SK58',1269,'Y',2622687,'bases','Micrococcus are Gram-positive cocci that are 0.5 to 3.5 micrometers in diameter and usually arranged in tetrads or irregular clusters. Micrococcus is generally thought of as harmless bacterium, but there have been rare cases of Micrococcus infections in people with compromised immune systems, as occurs with HIV patients. M. lutues can be mistaken for S. aureus. The two species share similar colony morphology as well as a similar yellow colony color. To distinguish between the two, a bacitracin test may be performed. M. lutues does not grow in the presence of bacitracin, and will leave a clear ring with no growth on the dish around the bacitracin disk. M. luteus is unique in its ability to absorb UV radiation. M. luteus has been isolated from human skin, animal and dairy products, and beer.','heterotrophic','lithotrophic','chemotrophic'),(660596,'Pantoea stewartii subsp. stewartii DC283',53335,'Y',5233214,'bases','\0P\0a\0n\0t\0o\0e\0a\0 \0s\0t\0e\0w\0a\0r\0t\0i\0i\0 \0i\0s\0 \0a\0 \0n\0o\0n\0m\0o\0t\0i\0l\0e\0,\0 \0f\0a\0c\0u\0l\0t\0a\0t\0i\0v\0e\0 \0a\0n\0a\0e\0r\0o\0b\0i\0c\0,\0 \0g\0r\0a\0m\0 \0n\0e\0g\0a\0t\0i\0v\0e\0,\0 \0r\0o\0d\0-\0s\0h\0a\0p\0e\0d\0 \0b\0a\0c\0t\0e\0r\0i\0u\0m\0 \0t\0h\0a\0t\0 \0c\0a\0u\0s\0e\0s\0 \0S\0t\0e\0w\0a\0r\0t \0s\0 \0w\0i\0l\0t\0 \0a\0n\0d\0 \0l\0e\0a\0f\0 \0b\0l\0i\0g\0h\0t\0 \0d\0i\0s\0e\0a\0s\0e\0 \0o\0n\0 \0m\0a\0i\0z\0e\0 \0(\0p\0a\0r\0t\0i\0c\0u\0l\0a\0r\0l\0y\0 \0s\0w\0e\0e\0t\0 \0c\0o\0r\0n\0)\0,\0 \0f\0l\0i\0n\0t\0,\0 \0d\0e\0n\0t\0,\0 \0f\0l\0o\0w\0e\0r\0,\0 \0a\0n\0d\0 \0p\0o\0p\0c\0o\0r\0n\0.\0 \0P\0a\0n\0t\0o\0e\0a\0 \0b\0a\0c\0t\0e\0r\0i\0a\0 \0a\0r\0e\0 \0y\0e\0l\0l\0o\0w\0 \0p\0i\0g\0m\0e\0n\0t\0e\0d\0,\0 \0f\0e\0r\0m\0e\0n\0t\0 \0l\0a\0c\0t\0o\0s\0e\0,\0 \0a\0r\0e\0 \0m\0o\0t\0i\0l\0e\0,\0 \0a\0n\0d\0 \0f\0o\0r\0m\0 \0m\0u\0c\0o\0i\0d\0 \0c\0o\0l\0o\0n\0i\0e\0s\0.\0 \0B\0e\0s\0i\0d\0e\0s\0 \0t\0h\0a\0t\0,\0 \0s\0o\0m\0e\0 \0o\0f\0 \0t\0h\0e\0 \0s\0p\0e\0c\0i\0e\0s\0 \0s\0h\0o\0w\0 \0q\0u\0o\0r\0u\0m\0 \0s\0e\0n\0s\0i\0n\0g\0 \0a\0b\0i\0l\0i\0t\0y\0 \0t\0h\0a\0t\0 \0c\0o\0u\0l\0d\0 \0d\0r\0i\0v\0e\0 \0d\0i\0f\0f\0e\0r\0e\0n\0t\0 \0g\0e\0n\0e\0 \0e\0x\0p\0r\0e\0s\0s\0i\0o\0n\0 \0h\0e\0n\0c\0e\0 \0c\0o\0n\0t\0r\0o\0l\0l\0i\0n\0g\0 \0c\0e\0r\0t\0a\0i\0n\0 \0p\0h\0y\0s\0i\0o\0l\0o\0g\0i\0c\0a\0l\0 \0a\0c\0t\0i\0v\0i\0t\0i\0e\0s\0.','heterotrophic','organotrophic','chemotrophic'),(904802,'Staphylococcus aureus subsp. aureus CO-98',1279,'Y',2515585,'bases','Staphylococci are spherical gram-positive bacteria, which are immobile and form grape-like clusters. They form bunches because they divide in two planes as opposed to their close relatives streptococci which form chains because they divide only in one plane. Colonies formed by S. aureus are yellow (thus the name aureus, Latin for gold) and grow large on a rich medium. Staphylococcus aureus and their genus Staphylococci are facultative anaerobes which means they grow by aerobic respiration or fermentation that produces lactic acid. Approximately 30% of the normal healthy population is affected by S. aureus as it asymptomatically colonizes on the skin of human hosts.','heterotrophic','organotrophic lithotrophic','chemotrophic'),(996285,'Pseudomonas stutzeri DSM 4166',286,'N',0,'bases','Pseudomonas stutzeri is a gram-negative bacterium that is known for its diverse metabolism. Individual P. stutzeri are rod-shaped and have a single polar flagellum. Cells are approximately 1-3um long and 0.5um in diameter. Colonies are disc shaped with ridges radiating from the center.','heterotrophic','organotrophic lithotrophic','chemotrophic'),(1138452,'Bacillus megaterium NCT-2',469,'Y',5323778,'bases','Bacillus megaterium is a rod-like, Gram-positive, mainly aerobic spore forming bacterium found in widely diverse habitats. With a cell length of up to 4 µm and a diameter of 1.5 µm, B. megaterium is amongst the biggest known bacteria. The cells often occur in pairs and chains, where the cells are joined together by polysaccharides on the cell walls. B. megaterium has been an important industrial organism for decades. It produces penicillin amidase used to make synthetic penicillin, various amylases used in the baking industry and glucose dehydrogenase used in glucose blood tests. Further, it is used for the production of pyruvate, vitamin B12, drugs with fungicidal and antiviral properties, etc.','heterotrophic','organotrophic lithotrophic','chemotrophic'),(1144661,'Acinetobacter sp. CIP 101934',286,'Y',3186404,'bases','Acinetobacter is a genus of Gram-negative bacteria belonging to the wider class of Gammaproteobacteria. Acinetobacter species are oxidase-negative and non-motile, and occur in pairs under magnification.\nThey are important soil organisms, where they contribute to the mineralization of, for example, aromatic compounds. Acinetobacter species are a key source of infection in debilitated patients in the hospital, in particular the species Acinetobacter baumannii.','heterotrophic','organotrophic','chemotrophic'),(1215114,'Pseudomonas parafulva NBRC 16636',286,'Y',4954362,'bases','Pseudomonas bacteria are generally aerobic rod-shaped bacteria that are known for their metabolic diversity. Some species of this bacteria, such as P. aeruginosa, are opportunistic pathogens that secrete extracellular proteases and adhere and invade host tissue. This bacteria is an opportunistic pathogen that affect humans, animals, and plants. Pseudomonas aeruginosa, called the \"epitome\" of opportunistic pathogens, almost never infects uncompromised tissues; however, it can infect practically any type of tissue if that tissue has some type of compromised defense. Pseudomonas species are also responsible for the spoilage of milk even after the process of pasteuriztion.','heterotrophic','organotrophic lithotrophic','chemotrophic'),(1219687,'Bacillus sp. 2385',1386,'N',0,'bases','Bacillus is a genus of gram-positive, rod-shaped (bacillus) bacteria and a member of the phylum Firmicutes. Bacillus species can be obligate aerobes (oxygen reliant), or facultative anaerobes (having the ability to be aerobic or anaerobic). They will test positive for the enzyme catalase when there has been oxygen used or present.Ubiquitous in nature, Bacillus includes both free-living (nonparasitic) and parasitic pathogenic species. Under stressful environmental conditions, the bacteria can produce oval endospores that are not true \'spores\', but to which the bacteria can reduce themselves and remain in a dormant state for very long periods.','heterotrophic','organotrophic lithotrophic','chemotrophic'),(1239307,'Sodalis sp.  HS1',84565,'Y',5159425,'bases','No information available as species unconfirmed and too much variation within the genus. (tsetse S-endosymbionts)','heterotrophic','organotrophic lithotrophic','chemotrophic'),(1305732,'Microbacterium sp. KROCY2',33882,'Y',2765822,'bases','high GC Gram+. No Species data available.','heterotrophic','No information','No information'),(1310833,'Acinetobacter baumannii 796380-1375',286,'Y',4146084,'bases','A. baumannii is an encapsulated Gram-negative coccobacilli bacteria that is generally non-motile. Previously named Acinetobacter calcoaceticus, it is an opportunistic pathogen found in soil and water. One of the first Acientobacter found in soil was discovered in 1911 by M.W. Beijerinck. In the 1970s A. baumannii was susceptible to common antibiotics, but has now developed into a multidrug-resistant bacteria, capable of acquiring resistance genes. One of the first antibiotic resistant strains of A. baumannii called carbapenem-resistant A. baumanni (CRAB) was isolated in 1991. A. baumannii generally affects patients with low immune systems, which has caused nosocomial infections and major concerns in hospitals given the ability of A. baumannii to live on a variety of hospital surfaces such as surgical drains and catheters.','heterotrophic','organotrophic','chemotrophic'),(1329833,'Enterobacter sp. MGH 37',547,'Y',5073939,'bases','Enterobacter bacteria are motile, rod-shaped cells, some of which are encapsulated. They also possess peritrichous flagella. Limited information as species unknown.','heterotrophic','organotrophic lithotrophic','chemotrophic'),(1329856,'Enterobacter cloacae UCICRE 12',547,'Y',5198067,'bases','\0E\0n\0t\0e\0r\0o\0b\0a\0c\0t\0e\0r\0 \0c\0l\0o\0a\0c\0a\0e\0 \0i\0s\0 \0a\0 \0r\0o\0d\0-\0s\0h\0a\0p\0e\0d\0,\0 \0g\0r\0a\0m\0-\0n\0e\0g\0a\0t\0i\0v\0e\0 \0b\0a\0c\0t\0e\0r\0i\0a\0 \0f\0r\0o\0m\0 \0t\0h\0e\0 \0E\0n\0t\0e\0r\0o\0b\0a\0c\0t\0e\0r\0i\0a\0c\0e\0a\0e\0 \0f\0a\0m\0i\0l\0y\0.\0 \0T\0h\0e\0 \0s\0i\0z\0e\0 \0o\0f\0 \0t\0h\0i\0s\0 \0b\0a\0c\0t\0e\0r\0i\0a\0 \0r\0a\0n\0g\0e\0s\0 \0f\0r\0o\0m\0 \00\0.\03\0-\00\0.\06\0 \0x\0 \00\0.\08\0-\02\0.\00\0 ¼\0m\0.\0 \0E\0n\0t\0e\0r\0o\0b\0a\0c\0t\0e\0r\0 \0c\0l\0o\0a\0c\0a\0e\0 \0a\0r\0e\0 \0n\0o\0s\0o\0c\0o\0m\0i\0a\0l\0 \0p\0a\0t\0h\0o\0g\0e\0n\0s\0 \0t\0h\0a\0t\0 \0c\0a\0n\0 \0c\0a\0u\0s\0e\0 \0a\0 \0r\0a\0n\0g\0e\0 \0o\0f\0 \0i\0n\0f\0e\0c\0t\0i\0o\0n\0s\0 \0s\0u\0c\0h\0 \0a\0s\0 \0b\0a\0c\0t\0e\0r\0e\0m\0i\0a\0,\0 \0l\0o\0w\0e\0r\0 \0r\0e\0s\0p\0i\0r\0a\0t\0o\0r\0y\0 \0t\0r\0a\0c\0t\0 \0i\0n\0f\0e\0c\0t\0i\0o\0n\0,\0 \0s\0k\0i\0n\0 \0a\0n\0d\0 \0s\0o\0f\0t\0 \0t\0i\0s\0s\0u\0e\0 \0i\0n\0f\0e\0c\0t\0i\0o\0n\0s\0,\0 \0u\0r\0i\0n\0a\0r\0y\0 \0t\0r\0a\0c\0t\0 \0i\0n\0f\0e\0c\0t\0i\0o\0n\0s\0,\0 \0e\0n\0d\0o\0c\0a\0r\0d\0i\0t\0i\0s\0,\0 \0i\0n\0t\0r\0a\0-\0a\0b\0d\0o\0m\0i\0n\0a\0l\0 \0i\0n\0f\0e\0c\0t\0i\0o\0n\0s\0,\0 \0s\0e\0p\0t\0i\0c\0 \0a\0r\0t\0h\0r\0i\0t\0i\0s\0,\0 \0o\0s\0t\0e\0o\0m\0y\0e\0l\0i\0t\0i\0s\0,\0 \0a\0n\0d\0 \0o\0p\0h\0t\0h\0a\0l\0m\0i\0c\0 \0i\0n\0f\0e\0c\0t\0i\0o\0n\0s\0.\0 \0E\0n\0t\0e\0r\0o\0b\0a\0c\0t\0e\0r\0 \0c\0l\0o\0a\0c\0a\0e\0 \0i\0n\0f\0e\0c\0t\0i\0o\0n\0s\0 \